revisions.rev:
[[Men who have sex with men]] (MSM) are often prohibited from donating [[blood donation|blood]] or tissue for [[Organ transplant|transplantation]] because they are considered to be at high risk for [[HIV]] and some types of [[hepatitis]], viruses that can be transmitted in [[blood transfusion]]s.  Restrictions on donors are often called "deferrals" since in some cases blood donors who are found ineligible may be accepted at a later date.

MSM is a classification of men who engage (or have engaged in the past) in sex with other men, regardless of whether they identify themselves as [[homosexual]], [[bisexual]] or [[heterosexual]].  Some organizations view the ban or restrictions on donation as [[homophobia]] or an infringement of the [[civil rights]] of the [[LGBT]] community since donations are rigorously [[HIV test|tested]] to rule out donors that are infected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeff-stier/blood-for-sale_b_52046.html |title=Blood for Sale |accessdate=2008-04-05 |last=Stier|first=Jeff |date=2007-06-13 |format=HTML |publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc}}</ref>  The restrictions vary from country to country, and in many cases men are deferred who have not had sex with men for many years.

The restrictions affect MSM and the female sex partners of MSM.  They do not otherwise affect women, including [[women who have sex with women]].

== MSM and HIV/AIDS ==
In many developed countries AIDS is more prevalent among MSM than among the general population.<ref>UNAIDS 2006 report on the global AIDS epidemic, [http://data.unaids.org/pub/GlobalReport/2006/2006_GR_CH05_en.pdf Chapter 05], June 2006</ref>  In the United States, MSM accounted for 49 percent of new HIV diagnoses reported in 2005.<ref>CDC [http://www.cdc.gov/hiv/topics/surveillance/resources/reports/2005report/pdf/2005SurveillanceReport.pdf HIV/AIDS Surveillance Report: HIV Infection and AIDS in the United States and Dependent Areas, 2005.]</ref> Some people claim that political correctness has led to the association of MSM and HIV being downplayed.<ref>James Chin, “The risks in hiding the HIV/AIDS truth”, ''Business Day'' (March 12, 2007), 9.</ref><ref>"The people punish Mr Blair", ''Daily Mail'' (UK) (May 6, 2005), 14.</ref>

